data.title: The Life and Legacy of Victor Hugo
data.meta_description: Learn about Victor Hugo's life, his role in French Romanticism, and his timeless works like Les Misérables.
data.text:
Victor Hugo's father was a general in Napoleon's army and his mother was a devout Catholic, providing him with a diverse perspective on politics and religion

Victor Hugo was greatly influenced by the works of Lord Byron, which shaped his development as a key proponent of the French Romantic movement

Victor Hugo's formative years were marked by the tumultuous era of Napoleonic France, which greatly influenced his literary themes

Victor Hugo's literary brilliance is evident in his masterpieces such as "Les Misérables" and "The Hunchback of Notre-Dame," which are celebrated for their exploration of human nature and social critiques

Hugo's commitment to human rights is reflected in his work as a member of the French National Assembly and Senate, advocating for the abolition of capital punishment and universal education

Despite being married, Victor Hugo engaged in notable extramarital relationships, including a long-standing liaison with Juliette Drouet

The loss of his daughter Léopoldine greatly affected Victor Hugo and influenced his emotionally charged poetry collection "Les Contemplations."

Victor Hugo's novels, particularly "Les Misérables" and "The Hunchback of Notre-Dame," have significantly influenced literary traditions and promoted the preservation of Gothic architecture in France

Hugo's insightful quotes continue to resonate with contemporary audiences, demonstrating his skill in expressing universal truths that transcend time and culture

Hugo's poetry broke free from neoclassical constraints and influenced future poets such as Charles Baudelaire and Arthur Rimbaud
